<Document>
<name>North Cascades Highway</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>North Cascades Highway</h2><p><i>Washington, USA · WA-20, Burlington to Winthrop</i></p><p><b>The 'American Alps' — 300+ glaciers, turquoise reservoirs, last all-weather highway built in lower-48.</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>182 km (113 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>3–4 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late May–mid October (closes Nov–Apr)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closed in winter (typically), no fuel between Marblemount and Mazama (140 km), snow possible Sept–June</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>332</td></tr></table><hr><p>Completed in 1972 — the last major all-weather highway built in the lower 48. The North Cascades hold more glaciers than anywhere else in the contiguous US (300+) and feel less like the Rockies than like the Alps. The pass closes from late November to April most years. The western entry through Newhalem is wet rainforest with bigleaf maple and red cedar; the eastern descent through Mazama is dry pine country. You cross a climate boundary in 50 km. Diablo Lake's surreal turquoise color is glacial flour suspended in meltwater.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Newhalem</b> — Company town for Seattle City Light, which dammed three lakes here. Trail of the Cedars (short loop) shows old-growth survivors.</li><li><b>Diablo Lake overlook</b> — Turquoise-green reservoir colored by suspended glacier flour from upstream. Best light midday when the color is most intense.</li><li><b>Ross Lake overlook</b> — 37 km reservoir extending into BC — only accessible by boat, float plane, or trail. No roads.</li><li><b>Rainy Pass</b> — 1,486 m. Pacific Crest Trail crosses here; 1.5 km loop to Rainy Lake (paved).</li><li><b>Washington Pass overlook</b> — 1,669 m. Liberty Bell Mountain framed in front of you — the route's signature photograph. Short paved path.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
